
[1]notary

   NO'TARY, n. [L. known.]

   1. Primarily, a person employed to take notes of contracts, trials and
   proceedings in courts among the Romans.

   2. In modern usage, an officer authorized to attest contracts or
   writings of any kind, to give them the evidence of authenticity. This
   officer is often styled notary public.
